body:
The function is a part of glibc: https://github.com/lattera/glibc/blob/master/iconv/iconv.h 
Glibc is included in every C/C++ program. 
I wonder how the linker didn't find it. 

I think, most likely, we should add this thing to our cmake file: https://cmake.org/cmake/help/latest/module/FindIconv.html

I will try to make a patch and ask you for helping me test it.
Sure, that sounds great; I will test the patch.

@iqbal-h , if you get a clean Ubuntu 22.04 environment, I believe the build will pass without problems.  When it failed, I think most likely the build environment has multiple "iconv.h" files. So, if you go to your build dir and run:
```
make clean
make VERBOSE=1 >& build.log
```
Then grep "string_normalizer.cc" in the build log, you will see the full build command that was used for compiling the source code. In the line you will see build options like "-I xxx -D xxx".  If you put all such options to the build command of the small test program I just provided, you should be able to reproduce the link error.  Then, search iconv.h in the folders that passed to "-I xxx" options. If you find any, open it and check if it has a license header. If it has a license says "GNU" something, that could be the reason.

@snnn, thanks for the detailed response.

When I build the code using `gcc -o t test.c -Wall -Wextra`, I get a lot of warnings and errors (shown in gist [here](https://gist.github.com/iqbal-h/610b9c46a13a038cdfaf68280cf17c0d))

`echo $?` command returns 1.

However, after building with `gcc t.c -o test.c -Wall -Wextra`, no errors or warnings occur, and the echo command returns 0.
Not sure if this modified build command should be used for the test in the first place.

You have "-I /home/wisn/anaconda3/envs/ml/include" in the compile command of string_normalizer.cc . And the iconv.h in the "/home/wisn/anaconda3/envs/ml/include" folder  is from GNU LIBICONV. That is the reason.

Since it was from anaconda environment, is it possible to using a new and clean environment for the build? Or you may consider using docker to isolate the work. ONNX Runtime's build scripts do not rely on anaconda. The python interpreter comes with the operating system should work fine.
@snnn Sounds good. Thanks for spotting the issue. I will create a new environment for the build and try again. I am closing the issue.
